div.p: A TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 refractory high entropy alloy was prepared by powder metallurgy and subsequently subjected to hot forging and annealing. Precipitation behavior and mechanical properties of the hotworked TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloy were investigated. Results show that the hot forging leads to a formation of (Zr, Al)-rich HCP precipitates in the initial BCC matrix. The precipitates have significant strengthening effect on the TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloy after annealing at 1000 °C for 2 h. Owing to the precipitation strengthening, the hot-worked TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloy exhibits a high compressive yield strength of 1740 MPa with a compressive stain of 20%. It is interesting that annealing at lower or higher temperatures than 1000 °C causes a degradation in compression properties, mainly due to the decomposition of the BCC matrix and the coarsening of the HCP precipitates.

div.head: Introduction
div.p: Refractory high entropy alloys (RHEAs) are a new class of multicomponent materials that have recently received much attention because of their attractive elevated-temperature mechanical properties [1][2][3]. RHEAs are generally based on five or more refractory metals, but may also contain other low density elements, and typically have a BCC crystal structure [4]. Generally, RHEAs exhibit high strength and hardness, mainly due to solid-solution strengthening and severe lattice distortion effect [5]. Further strengthening methods of RHEAs are usually associated with alloying, work hardening, grain-boundary strengthening and precipitation strengthening. Among these strategies, precipitation strengthening is considered as the most effectively method [6].

However, precipitation process of high entropy alloys is very slow due to sluggish diffusion effect. For example, the precipitation of a HCP phase in HfNbTaTiZr RHEA occurs after annealing for about 100 h [7], and the precipitation of a Cr-rich r phase in CrMnFeCoNi alloy needs an annealing time above 500 days [8]. Recently, it is reported that thermal mechanical processing can stimulate precipitation in high entropy alloys [9]. During deformation, crystalline defects such as vacancies, dislocations and stacking faults formed, promoting diffusion and leading to an earlier formation of precipitates [10]. Besides, hot deformation can eliminate casting defects and refine microstructures, and thus, improve mechanical properties of RHEAs. But up to now, there is very few research focusing on precipitation behavior of hotworked RHEAs. In this work, a TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 RHEA was prepared by powder metallurgy and subsequently subjected to hot forging and annealing. The precipitation behavior and its effects on mechanical properties were analyzed.

div.head: Experimental procedure
div.p: The as-sintered TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloy was prepared by powder metallurgy. The details of preparation process have been reported in our previous work [10]. Samples with a diameter of 30 mm and a height of 45 mm were machined from the as-sintered bulks, and then underwent hot forging at 1200 °C. The columnar samples were put in stainless steel cans to avoid severe oxidation during hot forging. The total height reduction is about 50%. After hot forging, the samples were annealed in vacuum at 600 °C $ 1200 °C for 2 h.

The phase analysis was performed by X-ray diffraction analyses (XRD, Advance D8) with Cu Ka radiation. The microstructures were observed by using a scanning electron microscope (SEM, Helios Nanolab G3 UC). The chemical composition was analyzed by energy dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDX). Specimens for SEM and EPMA were prepared from longitudinal cross-sections of the deformed samples. The details of microstructures were studied by using a transmission electron microscope (TEM, Titan G2 60-300). Specimens for TEM were prepared by using focused ion beam (FIB) apparatus. Compression tests were conducted on a hydraulic testing machine (Instron 8802) with a strain rate of 0.001 s À1 . Cylindrical specimens with dimension of 6 mm in diameter and 9 mm in height were used for compression tests.

div.head: Results and discussion
div.p: The XRD patterns of the TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloy in different status are shown in Fig. 1. The as-sintered alloy presents a BCC single phase structure. The lattice parameter of the BCC phase is determined to be 3.355 Å. A second phase with HCP crystal structure can be found after hot forging and subsequent annealing. Fig. 1b is the enlarged area of 30 $ 45 degree range of the XRD patterns. It should be noted that the BCC phase decomposes into BCC and BCC2 phases after annealing at 800 °C for 2 h. Similar decomposition behavior has been reported in RHEAs subjected to hot deformation at 800 °C [10].

Fig. 2 shows the microstructures of the TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloy. The single phase structure of the as-sintered TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloy is confirmed by the SEM observation (Fig. 2a). After hot forging, precipitates can be clearly found. The precipitates were identified as (Zr, Al)-rich phase (analyzed by EDX). Accompanied with the precipitation, a slight dynamic recrystallization (DRX) is also found. The alloy almost retained the hot-worked microstructures after annealing at 600 °C. But, annealing at 800 °C leads to a significant decomposition of the BCC matrix. The matrix transformed to single BCC phase when annealing at high temperatures (>1000 °C), however, the precipitates became coarser at higher annealing temperatures. The details of the precipitates were investigated by TEM as shown in Fig. 3. The grain size of the precipitates is about 1 lm.

The crystal structures of the precipitates (HCP) and DRX grains (BCC) are further verified by selected-area electron diffraction (SAED) as show in Fig. 3c andd. The BCC2 phase is plate-like with a size of about 50 nm, and is enriched in Ta and Nb.

According to the binary diagrams and the enthalpy of mixing between each two elements in Ti-Nb-Ta-Zr-Al system, Ta and Nb can form a BCC solid-solution phase at both low and high temperatures, while Zr and Al has a strong trend to form intermetallic phases [11,12]. As mentioned above, annealing at intermediate temperatures or thermal mechanical processing can stimulate precipitation in high entropy alloys. Therefore, the (Zr, Al)-rich HCP precipitates and the BCC2 phase could form either during hot forging or annealing. In addition, the HCP precipitates form continuous phase along grain boundaries with annealing temperatures increasing from 600 °C to 800 °C. But, when annealing at temperatures above 1000 °C, the precipitates become discontinuous again. This phenomenon is associated with the reversible wetting behavior, which has been also observed in a Cu-In system [13]. The formation of the network of brittle HCP phase may lead to limited ductility of the RHEA [14].

The compressive curves of the TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloy are shown in Fig. 4. The alloy is brittle after hot forging or annealing at 600 °C, possibly due to the insufficiently recrystallized microstructures. The alloy shows high yield strength after annealing at 800 °C, but, still has limited plasticity, because of the brittleness of the decomposed matrix. Apparently, annealing at 1000 °C for 2 h results in the best compression properties. The yield strength is 1740 MPa with a total strain of about 20%. In this condition, the precipitates are fine and distribute homogenously, while the matrix has been fully recrystallized with a single BCC solid solution. Annealing at higher temperature causes a degradation in both strength and plasticity. The coarsening of the HCP precipitates is responsible for the degraded properties.

div.head: Conclusion
div.p: Precipitation behavior and compression properties of the hotworked TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloy were investigated. The as-sintered alloy has a single BCC phase structure. The hot forging leads to a formation of (Zr, Al)-rich HCP precipitates. Owing to the precipitation strengthening, the hot-worked TiNbTa 0.5 ZrAl 0.5 alloy exhibits a high compressive yield strength of 1740 MPa with a total stain of 20% after annealing at 1000 °C for 2 h. Annealing at lower or higher temperatures than 1000 °C causes a degradation in compression properties, mainly due to the decomposition of the BCC matrix and the coarsening of the HCP precipitates.
